**Sec. 12A. Open Market Committee**

**(a) The Committee**  
A Federal Open Market Committee (the "Committee") is made. It has the Federal Reserve Board of Governors and five bank reps. These reps are bank presidents or vice-presidents. Each year, one is picked from different groups of Federal Reserve banks. The meetings are held in D.C. at least four times a year.

**(b) Banks Follow Rules**  
Fed banks must follow Committee rules for open-market moves. The Committee sets rules for these moves.

**(c) Buying and Selling Paper**  
The Committee decides when and how much paper to buy or sell, to help the economy and keep credit in check.
